``_negotiate_value()`` used ``re.compile`` every time it was called, which is

Significant refactor for 1.1.0 API

Rename kerberos module to kerberos_. Our kerberos module itself imports
kerberos, expecting to get the kerberos package, but it currently gets itself,
which means none of the kerberos library routines are actually available and
everything is a non-starter. This follows PEP8 for what to do when you have a
variable that conflicts with a builtin. Add a trailing _.

Handle errors more sensibly: If authentication fails, the server response will
be passed to the user. This is likely to be a 401. A 403 would indicate
successful authentication with an unauthorized user. If the client requires
mutual authentication (the default, similar to SSL certificate validation in
requests proper), an exception will be raised so that the user does not have the
opportunity to accept an untrusted response. If they're okay without requiring
mutual authentication, then they can specify that when constructing their
HTTPKerberosAuth object.

1.x API Change: Request objects no longer have a send mechanism. We need to
either generate a session and send with that or just use the connection
connected to the response object. This was essentially stolen from HTTPDigest
authentication.

Fix incorrect implementation of mutual authentication. Performing another
request during mutual authentication does not make sense. We're authenticating
the response we already received.

Allow different settings for mutual authentication:

  * REQUIRED: all responses will be authenticated with the exception of errors.
    Errors will have their contents and headers stripped. If a non-error
    response cannot be authenticated, a MutualAuthenticationError exception will
    be raised.
  * OPTIONAL: mutual authentication will be attempted if supported, and if
    supported and failed, a MutualAuthenticationError exception will be raised.
    Responses which do not support mutual authentication will be returned
    directly to the user.
  * DISABLED: mutual authentication will not be attempted, even if supported.

Support authentication of redirects, sanitize untrusted responses.

  * Track multiple contexts so that if/when we can authenticate redirects, we can
    support redirects to different hosts.
  * We want to be able to return unauthenticated errors to the user because they
    can be helpful in debugging, but we want to ensure that their content isn't
    used because the user is trusting us not to give them untrusted data. Hence
    the SanitizedResponse class.

Use user supplied options when retransmitting authenticated requests

Generate a test suite.

Supporting python 2.6+

Setup.py breaks if kerberos is not already installed.

When trying to install requests-kerberos setup.py cannot import
requets_kerberos.  Doing this causes a problem where requirements.txt
causes kerberos to be downloaded.  However, it is not yet installed
when requests-kerberos's setup.py is evaluated.  Since setup.py
imports requests_kerberos, and requests_kerberos import kerberos, the
installation fails.

See https://gist.github.com/pcn/5209734 for an example.

This commit fixes the problem by using the compiler module to parse
__init__.py, but doesn't evaluate it.  It then searches for the node
whose name is __version__ and uses the constant that would be assigned
to it for setup.py.

It does mean that version has to be a constant.  I don't think that'd
be a problem.

Remove REQUIRED, OPTIONAL, DISABLED from default exports

Prevent polluting the callers namespace with generically named constants.

Remove unnecessary commented lines

These were left over from when we required unittest2.

Version 0.2

I can fix up the README with history later and fix up PyPI to reflect it.

Handle additional uncaught GSSErrors

kerberos.authGSSClientStep() can raise a GSSError on a mutual authentication
failure instead of just setting the returncode to -1 as would be expected from
the underlying C library calls. Catch that GSSError and return False so that we
handle the mutual authentication failure appropriately.

Also, since every other kerberos call can raise a GSSError, prophylactically
wrap kerberos.authGSSClientResponse() in such a way as to prevent other
GSSErrors from reaching the user. In this case we'll return the 401 to the user
just as we do when authentication fails in other ways.

Fixing assertions regarding mocks not being called; resetting mocks

We need to reset mocks between tests if we want to be sure when we assert
whether or not they've been called and what they've been called with because if
we don't, they may have been called during other tests.

We mock.assert_not_called() isn't a thing, but it always returns a Truthy value
because it's a mock, and any method not defined will actually exist and return a
mock which is truthy. My head hurts. We need to assert that the special .called
parameter is False.

Test to ensure that authGSSClientStep during mutual auth raises the right exception.

Prevent regression of the leaking GSSError's we recently saw on mutual auth
failures.

Fix hangs on streaming uploads

After the server responds with a "401 Unauthorized",
requests_kerberos.HTTPKerberosAuth.handle_response() gets called and
it resends the request with "Authorization" header.

When doing streaming uploads, however, this gets stuck because the
body data (a file-like object) is already consumed at the first
attempt of sending the request and empty.

To fix this, rewind the file-like object to where it was before the
initial send call.

Prevent infinite recursion when GSSErrors occurs

When calling log.exception you do not need to pass an exception object,
it will fetch it from the stack automatically. Passing the exception
object in results in infinite recursion.

      File "/usr/lib64/python2.6/logging/__init__.py", line 1088, in exception
        self.error(*((msg,) + args), **{'exc_info': 1})
      File "/usr/lib64/python2.6/logging/__init__.py", line 1082, in error
        self._log(ERROR, msg, args, **kwargs)
      File "/usr/lib64/python2.6/logging/__init__.py", line 1173, in _log
        self.handle(record)
      File "/usr/lib64/python2.6/logging/__init__.py", line 1183, in handle
        self.callHandlers(record)
      File "/usr/lib64/python2.6/logging/__init__.py", line 1220, in callHandlers
        hdlr.handle(record)
      File "/usr/lib64/python2.6/logging/__init__.py", line 679, in handle
        self.emit(record)
      File "/usr/lib64/python2.6/logging/__init__.py", line 804, in emit
        self.handleError(record)
      File "/usr/lib64/python2.6/logging/__init__.py", line 733, in handleError

      File "/usr/lib64/python2.6/traceback.py", line 126, in print_exception
        lines = format_exception_only(etype, value)
      File "/usr/lib64/python2.6/traceback.py", line 179, in format_exception_only
